The paper discusses the design of prediction markets, which involves game theory and incentives for agents to reveal their information truthfully. This suggests that the paper is likely to belong to the Game Theory (cs.GT) sub-category. Additionally, the paper discusses the use of proper scoring rules, which are commonly used in machine learning and artificial intelligence (cs.AI) for evaluating probabilistic predictions. The paper also discusses the properties of different mechanisms, which suggests that it could belong to the Learning (cs.LG) or Data Structures and Algorithms (cs.DS) sub-categories. Finally, the paper draws connections to cooperative game theory, which suggests that it could also belong to the Economics and Computation (cs.EC) sub-category.
